Description: Defer virtual-monitor sizing until peerActivate fires.
 .
 Patch ``0002-virtual-monitor-from-client.patch`` introduced a
 ``--virtual-monitor client`` command-line mode whose
 ``SessionController::handleNewConnection`` reads
 ``peer->settings->DesktopWidth/Height`` (via
 ``RdpConnection::requestedDesktopSize()``) so that KWin's virtual
 output matches the size mstsc negotiated. The read was hung off the
 ``stateChanged(State::Running)`` signal on the theory that "by the
 time our queued-connection handler runs on the main thread, the
 FreeRDP capability exchange has completed and the settings struct
 has been populated".
 .
 That theory is not true in practice on Kubuntu 26.04 + FreeRDP
 3.24.2: ``setState(State::Running)`` is emitted in
 ``RdpConnection::run()`` *before* the server's main event loop has
 read a single byte from the client's socket (the ``while (!stopToken)``
 loop and the very first ``peer->CheckFileDescriptor()`` call both
 happen strictly after ``setState(Running)``). The queued signal
 therefore races with the FreeRDP connection-sequence, and in the
 common case our slot wins the race: the client's MCS Connect-Initial
 / Demand Active / Confirm Active PDUs haven't been processed yet,
 ``peer->settings->DesktopWidth/Height`` still hold FreeRDP's internal
 defaults (``1024x768``), and we create a virtual monitor at
 ``1024x768`` regardless of what the user picked in mstsc's Display
 tab.
 .
 The user-visible symptom is brutal: every RDP session comes up at
 1024x768 no matter what resolution the user selected, and on
 high-DPI clients (2560x1600, 3840x2160, ...) the streamed frame is
 unusably small once it's rescaled by the RDP client.
 .
 The fix is to use a signal that fires only after FreeRDP's own
 ``peerActivate`` callback -- i.e. after the client has sent
 Confirm Active and peer->settings carries its final, negotiated
 DesktopWidth/Height. We:
 .
   * Introduce ``RdpConnection::activated()``, a new Qt signal
     emitted from ``onActivate()`` (which is invoked from the
     FreeRDP ``peer->Activate`` callback right after a successful
     capability-exchange). Emission happens from the worker thread;
     the receiver's thread affinity determines dispatch semantics
     just like ``stateChanged``.
   * Switch ``SessionController::handleNewConnection`` to connect to
     ``activated()`` instead of ``stateChanged(Running)`` for the
     ``--virtual-monitor client`` code path.
 .
 ``State::Streaming`` would also work in principle (it fires after
 DRDYNVC_STATE_READY, which is strictly after activation), but it
 fires inside the run() loop *after* ``VideoStream::setEnabled(true)``
 -- by which point ``AbstractSession::start()`` has already been
 queued via the ``VideoStream::enabledChanged`` signal, so setting
 the virtual monitor at that point is too late. ``activated()`` is
 the smallest-scope, most specific hook.
 .
 This patch only affects the ``--virtual-monitor client`` code path;
 the explicit-size and no-virtual-monitor branches in
 ``handleNewConnection`` are unchanged.
